for pensions. we're going to take away their pensions if they violate our trust." (governor (candidate full), remarks at an ask mitt anything, urbandale, ia, 8/2/07) </p><p>- <em>to view governor (candidate last)'s full remarks, please see:</em> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5atxttlzw0">www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5atxttlzw0</a> </p></blockquote> <p><b>governor (candidate last) will prohibit family members of cabinet and senior staff members from lobbying the executive branch.</b> governor (candidate last): "presidents lead by example. and so, if i'm elected president, one of my first acts will be to issue an executive order prohibiting the immediate family of my cabinet and senior staff from lobbying the executive branch. the standard for high ethical conduct has to be set at the top." (governor (candidate full), remarks at the mackinac (PARTY NAME) leadership conference, mackinac, mi, 9/22/07) </p><p><b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s record of bringing higher ethical standards to government: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>governor (candidate last)'s administration "virtually scandal free and restrained in the exercise of patronage."</b> "(candidate last)'s obsession with maintaining a pure image annoyed many beacon hill regulars, but it produced an administration that was virtually scandal free and restrained in the exercise of patronage." (brian mooney, "taking office, remaining an outsider," <em>the boston globe</em>, 6/29/07) </p><p><b>in january 2003, governor (candidate last) issued an executive order requiring those applying for executive branch positions to identify family members working in state government.</b> "(candidate last) also issued an executive order putting in place so-called 'sunshine provisions' requiring new employees to identify family members working in state government. the 'sunshine provisions' in (candidate last)'s executive order require individuals applying for positions within the executive branch to disclose in writing the names of